Somalia.adaptation:
• **CGIAR** quantified climate-migration links in East Africa, showing droughts correlate with increased emigration (Source: **https://hdl.handle.net/10568/110278**);
• **Bioversity/CIAT** and **FAO Somalia** co-led a workshop to align climate, peace, and security policies (Source: **https://hdl.handle.net/10568/169331**);
• **CGIAR** mapped climate hazards (precipitation/temperature) for Somalia’s risk profiling (Source: **https://dataverse.harvard.edu/dataset.xhtml?persistentId=doi:10.7910/DVN/PKZ0G0**);
• **CGIAR** analyzed climate-induced conflict pathways (resource access, livelihoods, displacement) in Somalia (Source: **https://hdl.handle.net/10568/169463**);
• **CGIAR** trained African negotiators on attribution science for climate extremes (Source: **https://dataverse.harvard.edu/dataset.xhtml?persistentId=doi:10.7910/DVN/PKZ0G0**);
• **CGIAR** strengthened climate services for agriculture via institutional linkages (Source: **https://hdl.handle.net/10568/116941**);
• **CGIAR** supported UNHCR’s Regional Climate Action Plan (2023–2028) for adaptation measures (Source: **https://hdl.handle.net/10568/137370**);
• **ILRI/CGIAR** advanced livestock/pastoralism research for climate-resilient pastoral systems (Source: **https://hdl.handle.net/10568/128053**).

Bolivia.adaptation:
• **CCAFS** and **CIP** validated climate risks to Bolivia’s potato sector—including **temperature-induced growth disruptions** and **extreme weather events**—and recommended **hardy potato varieties**, sustainable cultivation practices, and **genetic diversity conservation** (e.g., **Parque de la Papa**) to mitigate impacts (Source: **https://hdl.handle.net/10568/65725**);
• **Bioversity International** (with PROINPA) found that **smallholder farmers’ use of crop diversity** (e.g., native potatoes) directly improves resilience to climate variability, informing **context-specific coping strategies** (Source: **https://hdl.handle.net/10568/52109**);
• **CCAFS** developed the **ILCYM phenology model** to predict **potato tuber moth (Phthorimaea operculella) infestation risks** under climate change, enabling **targeted pest management** in Bolivia, Peru, and Ecuador (Source: **https://dataverse.harvard.edu/dataset.xhtml?persistentId=doi:10.21223/P3/HYMGHM**);
• **CCAFS** and **FAO** implemented **Local Technical Agroclimatic Committees (LTACs)** in Bolivia to tailor **disaster risk management** for agriculture, aligning with regional strategies for food security (Source: **https://hdl.handle.net/10568/121200**);
• **CIP** launched the **WikiPapa platform**, a **citizen science tool** linking farmers, students, and researchers to document **800+ native potato varieties** from Bolivia, Peru, and Colombia, emphasizing **climate adaptation traits** (e.g., pest/disease resistance) and *in situ* conservation (Source: **https://dataverse.harvard.edu/dataset.xhtml?persistentId=doi:10.21223/OTJ1PV**);
• **CCAFS** assessed **on-farm conservation projects** in Bolivia’s High Andes, revealing their role in preserving **genetic resources** and **livelihood diversification** for smallholders (Source: **https://dataverse.harvard.edu/dataset.xhtml?persistentId=doi:10.7910/DVN/26678**);
• **CCAFS** surveyed **gender differences in crop diversity use** for climate adaptation in Bolivia (Cochabamba/La Paz), contributing to **indigenous knowledge databases** for resilient seed systems (Source: **https://dataverse.harvard.edu/dataset.xhtml?persistentId=doi:10.7910/DVN/XYKYDW**).
